inguishes itself by the wide range and scope of its themes, voices and approaches. Thirty-five leading essayists, literary critics and writing instructors explore the essay from multiple perspectives, including its theories, forms and histories as well as its cultural, political and pedagogical contexts. In particular, the volume extends the theory of the essay by addressing topics such as the construction of an essayistic self and the political dimensions of essaying. It further explores the relationship between the essay and other forms, such as philosophical writing, the column, science writing, the novel, the lyric and the advert as well as the essay in digital spaces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAquilina, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAquilina, Mario, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBorg, Kurt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBugliani, Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallus, Ivan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChamberlain, Elizabeth F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChilds, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCowser, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Glenn Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHesse, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHopper, Briallen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoy, Pat C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc